# Sphagnum Moss
#home/gardening/indoor-gardening/houseplants 

![](data:image/png;base64,)
## Summary
Sphagnum moss is a genus of 380 recognized mosses that primarily grow on the top of peat bogs. It is also called peat moss, bog moss, and quacker moss. This can lead to some confusion when purchasing it, as peat is often sold as sphagnum peat moss and under other similar names. It is used as a substrate and soil amendment in horticulture. Sphagnum is exceptionally suited to applications where water retention is preferred, as it retains up to 18x its own weight in water. Sphagnum has a neutral pH, and is a sterile growing medium, providing no nutrients to plants.

## Purchasing
Purchasing sphagnum moss can be complicated by a number of different factors, including confusion over naming, the fact that it can be purchased fresh or dried, and the wide variability in quality of sphagnum moss available. Additionally, many other types of cheaper mosses are often sold erroneously as sphagnum moss. Add to this the fact that a lot of sphagnum moss is unethically and sometimes illegally poached from peat bogs in the wild instead of sustainably farmed, and purchasing real sphagnum moss ethically and cheaply becomes difficult.

Most sphagnum moss is sold dried, in bales or bags. It can be sold in a milled form or in long strands (aka, Long Fiber Sphagnum or LFS). Depending on the application, LFS is generally preferable.

## Growing Sphagnum
It is easy to grow your own sphagnum moss at home if you are interested in creating a self-sufficient supply of it. In order to grow it at home, you need to first buy some live LFS. You then have many options for how to grow it. Professional growers tend to grow it on fiberglass trays. I have grown it in a large nursery pot which I kept in a sealed plastic bag under grow lights. I turned the sphagnum and sprayed it with water every few weeks. It grows relatively slowly, but steadily. I also grew some by snipping off the heads (capitulums) and sticking them in [Coco Peat](Coco%20Peat.md). 

## Using Sphagnum as a Substrate
Sphagnum moss works excellently as a growing substrate due to its highly absorbent and water retentive properties. I have found that it works best when paired with perlite, usually in a mix of about half sphagnum and half perlite. The perlite provides some much-needed aeration to the sphagnum and prevents the substrate from becoming anaerobic. 

Some people use sphagnum for propagation purposes only, while others will use it as the final growing media. Since sphagnum is nearly sterile, fertilization is required when it is used as a long term substrate.
